Cyrus_the_Great of Achaemenid_Empire commonly known as Cyrus_the_Great the Great and also called Cyrus_the_Great the Elder by the Ancient_Greece, was the founder of the Achaemenid Empire, the first Persian Empire. Under his rule, the empire embraced all the previous civilized states of the Near_East East, expanded vastly and eventually conquered most of Western_Asia and much of Central_Asia and the Caucasus. From the Mediterranean_Sea and Dardanelles in the west to the Indus_River in the east, Cyrus_the_Great the Great created the List_of_largest_empires the world had yet seen.Under his successors, the empire eventually stretched at its maximum extent from parts of the Balkans (Bulgaria-Paeonia and Thrace-Macedonia) and Eastern_Europe proper in the west, to the Indus_River in the east. His regal titles in full were The_Great_King, King of Achaemenid_Empire, King of Anshan, King of Media, King of Babylon, King of Sumer and Akkadian_Empire, and King of the Four_Corners of the World. The Nabonidus_Chronicle notes the change in his title from simply "King of Anshan", a City, to "King of Achaemenid_Empire". Assyria François Vallat wrote that "When Astyages marched against Cyrus_the_Great, Cyrus_the_Great is called ‘King of Anshan’, but when Cyrus_the_Great crosses the Tigris on his way to Lydia, he is ‘King of Achaemenid_Empire’. The coup therefore took place between these two events."

The reign of Cyrus_the_Great the Great lasted c. 30 years. Cyrus_the_Great built his empire by first conquering the Median Empire, then the Lydian Empire, and eventually the Neo-Babylonian Empire. He led an expedition into Central_Asia, which resulted in major campaigns that were described as having brought "into subjection every nation without exception".Cyrus_the_Great did not venture into Ancient_Egypt, and was alleged to have died in Battle, fighting the Massagetae along the Syr_Darya in December 530 BC. He was succeeded by his son, Cambyses_II, who managed to add to the empire by conquering Ancient_Egypt, Nubia, and Cyrenaica during his short rule.

Cyrus_the_Great the Great respected the customs and religions of the lands he conquered. This became a very successful model for centralized administration and establishing a government working to the advantage and profit of its subjects.In fact, the administration of the empire through satraps and the vital principle of forming a government at Pasargadae were the works of Cyrus_the_Great II.What is sometimes referred to as the Edict of Bourbon_Restoration (actually two edicts) described in the Hebrew_Bible as being made by Cyrus_the_Great the Great left a lasting legacy on the Jews religion, where, because of his policies in Babylonia, he is referred to by the Hebrew_Bible as Messiah (lit. "His anointed one") (Book_of_Isaiah 45:1), and is the only non-Jewish figure in the Hebrew_Bible to be called so.

Cyrus_the_Great the Great is also well recognized for his achievements in Human_rights, politics, and military strategy, as well as his influence on both Eastern and Western civilizations. Having originated from Persis, roughly corresponding to the modern Iranian province of Fars, Cyrus_the_Great has played a crucial role in defining the national identity of modern History_of_Iran. The Achaemenid_Empire influence in the ancient world eventually would extend as far as Classical_Athens, where upper-class Athenians adopted aspects of the culture of the ruling class of Achaemenid_Empire Achaemenid_Empire as their own.

In the 1970s, the last List_of_monarchs_of_Persia of History_of_Iran Mohammad_Reza_Pahlavi identified his famous proclamation inscribed onto the Cyrus_Cylinder as the oldest known declaration of Human_rights, and the Cylinder has since been popularized as such. This view has been criticized by some historians as a misunderstanding of the Cylinder's generic nature as a traditional statement that new monarchs make at the beginning of their reign.

