The name Cyrus_the_Great is a Latin form derived from the Greek_language Κῦρος, Kỹros, itself from the Old_Persian Kūruš.The name and its meaning has been recorded in ancient inscriptions in different languages. The Greek_language historians Ctesias and Plutarch noted that Cyrus_the_Great was named from Kuros, the Ra, a concept which has been interpreted as meaning "like the Ra" (Khurvash) by noting its relation to the Persian_language Noun for sun, khor, while using -vash as a Suffix of likeness. This may also point to a fascinating relationship to the mythological "first king" of Achaemenid_Empire, Jamshid, whose name also incorporates the element "sun" ("shid").

Karl_Hoffmann_(linguist) has suggested a translation based on the meaning of an Indo-European-root "to humiliate" and accordingly "Cyrus_the_Great" means "humiliator of the enemy in verbal contest". In the Persian_language and especially in History_of_Iran, Cyrus_the_Great's name is spelled . In the Bible, he is known as Koresh.

